column8:
First, I compared the charts between the unlabeled connection against the other two provided by the system. Then, I checked the destination port the connection used (and if I wasn't immediately familiar with it, I googled it) to try to understand the type of data of the connection. After that, I looked up information about the destination IP to try to understand the purpose of the connection. In some cases, the IP was already part of a list of addresses showing bad or suspicious behaviour. Finally, I filtered the list by destination, and origin IP, to check if other connections had been labeled as malicious.
If by then the connection wasn't obviously normal to me, I checked if it was similar to the one provided by the system as a botnet connection, and I tagged it as such.
At first, I also checked the sequences, but I quickly found out that it was easier to interpret the charts.
column9:
I followed the same steps as previously detailed. If the flow was mostly periodical, and if the destination IP was not immediately suspicious, I compared it with the botnet example, and if it had no similarities, I labeled it as normal.
For example, in one connection I saw that the destination IP belonged to Canonical, the periodicity was strong, and the size was large, so I assumed that it was a software download, and thus most likely a legitimate connection, .
